CLI Dependency Management

  Starting with version 3.11.0, the Maven Dependency Plugin provides three goals
  for managing dependencies directly from the command line: <<<dependency:add>>>,
  <<<dependency:remove>>>, and <<<dependency:search>>>.

* Adding Dependencies

  The <<<dependency:add>>> goal adds a dependency to your project's <<<pom.xml>>>.

** Basic Usage

  You can add a dependency by specifying its coordinates individually:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -DgroupId=com.google.code.gson -DartifactId=gson -Dversion=2.10.1
+---+

  Or use the shorter <<<gav>>> shorthand format:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1
+---+

  The <<<gav>>> parameter accepts the format <<<groupId:artifactId[:version[:scope[:type[:classifier]]]]>>>.
  For example, to add a test-scoped dependency:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1:test
+---+

  You can also specify <<<scope>>> separately:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1 -Dscope=test
+---+

** Adding to dependencyManagement

  Use the <<<-Dmanaged>>> flag to add a dependency to the <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>> section
  instead of <<<\<dependencies\>>>>:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1 -Dmanaged
+---+

** Adding a BOM Import

  To import a BOM (Bill of Materials) into <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>>, use the <<<-Dbom>>> flag:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-dependencies:3.2.0 -Dbom
+---+

  This inserts a dependency with <<<type=pom>>> and <<<scope=import>>> into <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>>.

** Version Inference

  When adding to <<<\<dependencies\>>>> and the version is already managed by a parent POM's
  <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>>, you can omit the version:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson
+---+

  The goal will detect the managed version and omit the <<<\<version\>>>> element from the inserted
  dependency, following Maven convention. If no managed version is found, the goal fails with
  a descriptive error.

** Additional Parameters

  You can also specify <<<type>>> and <<<classifier>>> explicitly. These override any values
  provided in the <<<gav>>> shorthand:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.example:lib:1.0 -Dtype=test-jar
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.example:lib:1.0 -Dclassifier=sources
+---+

** Updating an Existing Dependency

  By default, <<<dependency:add>>> fails if the dependency already exists. Use <<<-DupdateExisting>>>
  to update it instead:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.11.0 -DupdateExisting
+---+

  When updating, you can clear existing fields by setting them to <<<NONE>>>:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.11.0 -Dscope=NONE -DupdateExisting
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.11.0 -Dtype=NONE -DupdateExisting
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.11.0 -Dclassifier=NONE -DupdateExisting
+---+

  The <<<NONE>>> sentinel removes the corresponding XML element from the dependency.
  Fields not specified are left unchanged.

** Scope Validation

  The <<<scope>>> parameter is validated against Maven's known scope values:
  <<<compile>>>, <<<provided>>>, <<<runtime>>>, <<<test>>>, <<<system>>>, and <<<import>>>.
  Invalid scope values are rejected with an error.

** Multi-Module Projects

  To add a dependency to a specific child module from the root of a multi-module project,
  use the <<<-Dmodule>>> parameter:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1 -Dmodule=my-service
+---+

** Adding to a Profile

  To add a dependency to a specific Maven profile, use the <<<-Dprofile>>> parameter.
  If the profile does not exist, it is created automatically:

+---+
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1 -Dprofile=dev
mvn dependency:add -Dgav=org.mockito:mockito-core:5.0.0 -Dscope=test -Dprofile=test-support
+---+

* Removing Dependencies

  The <<<dependency:remove>>> goal removes a dependency from your project's <<<pom.xml>>>.

** Basic Usage

  Remove a dependency using the <<<gav>>> shorthand:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson
+---+

  Or using explicit coordinates:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -DgroupId=com.google.code.gson -DartifactId=gson
+---+

  Only <<<groupId>>> and <<<artifactId>>> are required to identify the dependency to remove.

** Type and Classifier Matching

  When multiple variants of a dependency exist (e.g., jar and test-jar), use <<<-Dtype>>>
  and <<<-Dclassifier>>> to target a specific one:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -DgroupId=com.example -DartifactId=lib -Dtype=test-jar
mvn dependency:remove -DgroupId=com.example -DartifactId=lib -Dclassifier=sources
+---+

  Explicit <<<-Dtype>>> and <<<-Dclassifier>>> override any values from the <<<-Dgav>>> shorthand.

** Removing a BOM Import

  To remove a BOM import from <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>>, use the <<<-Dbom>>> flag:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -Dgav=org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-dependencies -Dbom
+---+

  This is equivalent to <<<-Dmanaged -Dtype=pom>>>.

** Removing from dependencyManagement

  To remove a dependency from <<<\<dependencyManagement\>>>> instead of <<<\<dependencies\>>>>:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson -Dmanaged
+---+

** Removing from a Specific Module

  In a multi-module project, target a specific child module:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson -Dmodule=my-service
+---+

  If the dependency is not found, the goal fails with a descriptive error message.

** Removing from a Profile

  To remove a dependency from a specific Maven profile:

+---+
mvn dependency:remove -Dgav=com.google.code.gson:gson -Dprofile=dev
+---+

* Searching Maven Central

  The <<<dependency:search>>> goal queries Maven Central for matching artifacts. This goal
  does not require a project — it can be run from any directory.

  By default, search runs in <interactive mode>: results are shown as a numbered list,
  and you can select an artifact to browse its versions and get the <<<dependency:add>>>
  command. To disable interactive mode (e.g., for scripting), pass <<<-Dinteractive=false>>>.

** Basic Usage

+---+
mvn dependency:search -Dquery=gson
+---+

  In interactive mode, you'll see a numbered list and be prompted to select an artifact,
  then a version. After selection, the goal prints the <<<dependency:add>>> command.

  The following commands are available at any prompt:

  * <<<q>>> or <<<quit>>> — exit interactive mode

  * <<<b>>> or <<<back>>> — return to the previous list (version selection only)

  * Any text — triggers a new search with that text

  []

  In non-interactive mode (<<<-Dinteractive=false>>>), a table is displayed:

+---+
[INFO] Search results for: gson
[INFO]
[INFO]   groupId                  artifactId          latest version
[INFO]   ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
[INFO]   com.google.code.gson     gson                2.10.1
[INFO]
[INFO] 1 result(s) found. Use dependency:add to add one to your project:
[INFO]   mvn dependency:add -Dgav="com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10.1"
+---+

** Structured Queries

  You can search by groupId or artifactId using structured query syntax:

+---+
mvn dependency:search -Dquery="g:com.google.code.gson"
mvn dependency:search -Dquery="a:gson"
mvn dependency:search -Dquery="g:com.google AND a:gson"
+---+

** Limiting Results

  Use <<<-Drows>>> to control the number of results returned:

+---+
mvn dependency:search -Dquery=jackson -Drows=20
+---+

** Custom Repository Endpoint

  To search against a private registry that exposes a compatible search API:

+---+
mvn dependency:search -Dquery=my-lib -DrepositoryUrl=https://nexus.example.com/solrsearch/select
+---+

** Disabling Interactive Mode

  Interactive mode is enabled by default when a console is available. To disable it
  (e.g., for CI pipelines or scripts), use <<<-Dinteractive=false>>>:

+---+
mvn dependency:search -Dquery=gson -Dinteractive=false
+---+
